I've found the root cause of the horizontal overflow! It was a classic CSS Grid "blowout" issue. 

In CSS Grid, child elements have a default `min-width: auto`, which means they won't shrink smaller than the intrinsic width of their content (in this case, the wide incidents table). This completely bypassed the `overflow-x: auto` on the table's container. By explicitly setting `min-width: 0` on the grid children in `global.css`, the grid layout is allowed to shrink to the viewport size, enabling the table's scroll container to work properly on mobile.

I'm rerunning the accessibility test one more time to confirm.
I'm happy to report that the mobile overflow issue has been successfully resolved! The CSS grid blowout was fixed by enforcing `min-width: 0` on all grid items in `global.css`, which allows the table's scroll container to work properly on smaller viewports.

